Do *not* use string processing tools to process XML! XML is not a regular format, and using `str.replace()` or `sed` or any such tools is likely to lead to false positives and errors.

Use an XML parser; Python has [`xml.etree.ElementTree`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/xml.etree.elementtree.html) which makes this task simple enough:

    from pathlib import Path
    from xml.etree import ElementTree as ET

    for xmlfile in Path(&quot;directory_with_xml_files&quot;).glob(&quot;*.xml&quot;):
        tree = ET.parse(xmlfile)
        namespace = tree.getroot().tag.partition(&#39;}&#39;)[0][1:]
        elem = tree.find(f&quot;.//a:fileName&quot;, {&#39;a&#39;: namespace})
        elem.text = f&quot;{xmlfile.stem}.tiff&quot;
        tree.write(xmlfile, default_namespace=namespace,
                   encoding=&quot;UTF-8&quot;, xml_declaration=True)

The above processes all XML files in a given directory (using the [`pathlib` module](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html), finding XML files using the [`Path.glob()` method](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html#pathlib.Path.glob)). For each file, it parses the XML data into an XML tree, finds the first `&lt;fileName&gt;` element in the tree using a simple [XPath expression](https://docs.python.org/3/library/xml.etree.elementtree.html#elementtree-xpath), [updates the text](https://docs.python.org/3/library/xml.etree.elementtree.html#modifying-an-xml-file) of that element (using the [filename stem](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html#pathlib.PurePath.stem), which is the base name without the `.xml` extension) and writes out the XML tree back to the original file.

You stated you use an [ALTO schema](https://www.loc.gov/standards/alto/), which uses [XML namespaces](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XML_namespace) to distinguish between versions; the above should pick up the correct namespace to use from the root element, then uses that namespace (with `a` as the prefix) in the XPath query.

